{"cursor":"4591","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox artery\n| Name = Arch of aorta, aortic arch Latin = Arcus aortae GraySubject = 142\n| GrayPage = 547 Image = Gray506.svg Caption = The thoracic aorta with its major\n| branches. Note the large vessels sprouting from the arch Image2 = Gray505.png\n| Caption2 = The aortic arch and its branches shown [[In situ#Medicine|in\n| situ]]. BranchFrom = Ascending aorta BranchTo =\nBrachiocephalic trunk Left common carotid artery Left subclavian artery\nContinues as descending aorta, thoracic part\n| Vein = Combination of superior and inferior vena cava Precursor = Fourth left\n| pharyngeal arch artery Supplies = The entire body, with exception of the\n| respiratory zone of the lung and the heart. MeshName = Aortic+Arch |\n| transverse+aortic+arch MeshNumber = A07.231.114.056.372. DorlandsPre = a_58\n| DorlandsSuf = 12150514\n}}\n\nThe 'arch of the aorta' or the 'transverse aortic arch' ( [[OED]] 2nd\nedition, 1989, as . [http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/aortic\nEntry \"aortic\"] in [http://www.merriam-webster.com/ Merriam-Webster Online\nDictionary]. ) is the part of the aorta that begins at the level of the\nupper border of the second sternocostal articulation of the right side, and runs\nat first upward, backward, and to the left in front of the trachea; it is then\ndirected backward on the left side of the trachea and finally passes downward on\nthe left side of the body of the fourth thoracic vertebra, at the lower border\nof which it becomes continuous with the descending aorta.\n\nIt thus forms two curvatures: one with its convexity upward, the other with its\nconvexity forward and to the left. Its upper border is usually about\n2.5Â cm. below the superior border to the manubrium sterni.\n\nComing out of the heart, the thoracic aorta has a maximum dimension of 4 cm at\nthe root. By the time it becomes the ascending aorta, the diameter should be Acad Radiol. 2008 Jul;15(7):827-\n34.do